com.yahoo.bullet.record

Class BulletRecord

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.yahoo.bullet.record.BulletRecord
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Iterable<Map.Entry<String,Object>>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AvroBulletRecord, SimpleBulletRecord

    public abstract class BulletRecord
extends Object
implements Iterable<Map.Entry<String,Object>>, Serializable
    Data sent to Bullet should be wrapped in a class that extends this abstract class. It is Serializable and Iterable so records can be used in for-each loops. The various set methods can be used to insert fields into the record. They are implemented by default to use the base set(String, Object) method which should be overridden in child classes. Field names are to be provided as Strings and must be unique, otherwise the duplicate takes precedence over the first by default. When inserting into the Record, methods are explicitly provided for each type supported (listed below). When reading from the Record, which may not be something needed by users of this very frequently (as it is the entry point into Bullet), a generic Object is returned instead. Casting it is left to the user. The record currently supports these fields: 
     Primitives: Boolean, Integer, Long, Float, Double, String
 Complex:  Map <String, "Primitives">, Map<String, Map<String, "Primitives">>, List<"Primitives">,
           List<Map<String, "Primitives">> where "Primitives" refers to the afore-mentioned Primitives.
    Instead of setting a field to null (you cannot for top level Java primitives), avoid setting it instead.
    See Also:

      • extractField

        public Object extractField(String identifier)
        Gets a field from the record by identifier.

        For example, suppose a record has a map of boolean maps called "aaa". Then
        - "aaa" identifies that map of maps
        - "aaa.bbb" identifies the inner map that "aaa" maps "bbb" to (if it exists)
        - "aaa.bbb.ccc" identifies the boolean that "aaa.bbb" (if it exists) maps "ccc" to (if it exists)

        For a list element, the index is the key, e.g. "my_list.0" or "my_list.0.some_key"
        Parameters:
        identifier - The non-null identifier of the field to get.
        Returns:
        The value of the field or null if it does not exist.
